    "question_id" : 8295999,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Either copy elements one at a time in a loop or use <code>System.arraycopy</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Understand that an array in Java is like an array in C in that it's fixed length (there are other classes like ArrayList for variable-length use).  So you don't \"add\" a new element, you simply assign a value (<code>x[i] = something;</code>) to an existing element (which was initialized to zero when the array was created).</p>\n\n<p>To my knowledge there's no \"add all elements of this array\" method on ArrayList, so to do that you'd have to loop through the array and add the elements one at a time.  There are methods to go the other direction.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 963389,
      "reputation" : 11968,
      "user_id" : 987244,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/ueis0.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "shift66",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/987244/shift66"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1322484520,
    "creation_date" : 1322484520,
    "answer_id" : 8296031,
    "question_id" : 8295999,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>        int[] newarray = new int[] {1,2,3,4}  \n        int[] result = new int[newarray.length];\n        for(int i=0;i&lt;newarray.length;i++)\n            result[i]=newarray[i];\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 412934,
      "reputation" : 20147,
      "user_id" : 786284,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 87,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d4760a338973ba6d465a5e1e95d187f1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Jan Vorcak",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/786284/jan-vorcak"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1322484672,
    "creation_date" : 1322484672,
    "answer_id" : 8296066,
    "question_id" : 8295999,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>System.arraycopy(newarray, 0, result, 0, newarray.length);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or you can do it manually </p>\n\n<pre><code>for(int i = 0; i &lt; newarray.length; i++) {\n    result[i] = newarray[i];\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>to work with Arrays, you can use</p>\n\n<pre><code>Arrays.asList(Object[] a);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 88014,
      "reputation" : 62762,
